<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ880908-0015 </DOCNO><HL> What's News -- Business and Finance </HL><SO>  </SO><TEXT>   THE SEC CHARGED Drexel Burnham, its junk-bond chief Michael Milken and others with insider trading and other securities violations. The 184-page complaint accuses the defendants of using Ivan Boesky's organization as a front for a series of illegal schemes. The defendants include corporate raider Victor Posner.    A tougher insider-trading law may be more likely to pass Congress this year because of the SEC charges. But the case isn't expected to cause unusual turmoil in financial markets.    ---   ATandamp;T plans to eliminate as many as 6,000 jobs in its long-distance phone network by 1990 to reduce costs. The company said it will try to avoid outright layoffs &quot;at all costs.&quot;    ---   The Bass Group has agreed to restrict merchant banking activities as part of its acquisition of American Sandamp;L, sources said. The thrift's former parent, Financial Corp. of America, announced it will file for Chapter 11 reorganization, as expected.    ---   The Senate Finance panel is expected to approve a package today that would raise about $2 billion in taxes and extend some expiring tax breaks. The action is designed to allow the Senate to take up the tax legislation as early as next week.    ---   American Stores' merger of supermarket chains resulting from its $2.51 billion acquisition of Lucky Stores was temporarily blocked by a federal judge. The action came in response to an antitrust suit by California.    ---   Morgan Stanley ex-analyst Stephen Wang pleaded guilty to criminal insider trading charges. Wang and businessman Fred Lee were charged in an SEC civil case in June.    ---   Campeau moved to further reduce debt by agreeing to sell its Gold Circle discount chain to a shopping center developer. It is Campeau's seventh asset sale since it bought Federated for $6.6 billion in May.    ---   Marriott plans to invest $1 billion over five years to more than double its stake in extended-stay hotels, the fastest growing area of the industry.    ---   Browning-Ferris named former EPA head William Ruckelshaus as its chairman and chief executive, partly to boost its environmental image.    ---   Hoffmann-La Roche said the FDA approved its program designed to prevent birth defects caused by its prescription acne drug Accutane.    ---   Peru announced a major austerity program to ease inflation and a foreign-exchange shortage and improve relations with foreign creditors.    ---   The European economy appears to be stronger than expected, reflecting strong consumer demand and a surge in business investment.    ---   France plans to list some of its treasury bonds on the New York Stock Exchange in the form of ADRs.    ---   U.S. commercial banks posted a robust $5.5 billion in earnings for the second quarter, boosting first-half net income to a record $10.5 billion.    ---   Markets --   Stocks: Volume 139,590,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials 2065.79, up 0.53; transportation 866.94, off 2.24; utilities 180.00, off 0.54.    Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 1238.35, off 1.25.    Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 137.88, up 0.55; spot index 133.55, off 0.22.    Dollar: 133.47 yen, off 1.41; 1.8431 marks, up 0.0013. </TEXT></DOC>